---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="How Solid Is This?">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">

    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="text-center mb-12">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4">How Solid Is This?</h1>
      <p class="text-xl themed-text-muted">A Confidence Map</p>
    </header>

    <!-- Intro -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <p class="themed-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">Every claim below carries the status tag the framework gives it. The tags are not decoration — they are the whole point. <span class="font-mono text-sm">[derived]</span> means proven in the math chain, <em>given the stated premises</em>. <span class="font-mono text-sm">[candidate]</span> means not yet earned. <span class="font-mono text-sm">[falsifiable]</span> means it could kill the framework. <span class="font-mono text-sm">[open]</span> means unresolved.</p>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary leading-relaxed">Nothing here is sealed. The framework's one named lemma-candidate — L1, "no unframed distinction" — is the open head of the audit, and it carries four separate loads. If it fails, a great deal re-inflates.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Derived -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2" style="color: var(--color-strong);">[derived]</h2>
      <p class="themed-text-muted mb-6 italic">Proven in the math chain — given the premises named in each row</p>

      <div class="themed-surface border rounded-lg p-6 overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full text-left">
          <thead>
            <tr class="themed-border border-b">
              <th class="pb-3 themed-text-muted">Claim</th>
              <th class="pb-3 themed-text-muted">Given</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="themed-text-secondary">
            <tr class="themed-border-light border-b">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 align-top"><strong>The slice identity</strong><br /><span class="text-sm themed-text-muted">One law, two real slices: the circle and the hyperbola are faces of a single conservation statement. The gradient <em>is</em> the orbit.</span></td>
              <td class="py-3 align-top">P1, L1</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="themed-border-light border-b">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 align-top"><strong>i² = −1</strong><br /><span class="text-sm themed-text-muted">Reached by two independent routes — elimination, and antipodal binding — which survive deletion of each other.</span></td>
              <td class="py-3 align-top">P1, L1</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="themed-border-light border-b">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 align-top"><strong>The standoff</strong><br /><span class="text-sm themed-text-muted">The interior is not floor-forbidden but excluded by constitution. There is no <em>through</em>, only <em>around</em>.</span></td>
              <td class="py-3 align-top">P1, L1, Definition T</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 align-top"><strong>Index-relationality</strong><br /><span class="text-sm themed-text-muted">Frame indices name relations — parent-of, child-of — never absolute positions. The nesting is a tree, not a ladder.</span></td>
              <td class="py-3 align-top">P1, L1</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Candidate -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2" style="color: var(--color-plausible);">[candidate]</h2>
      <p class="themed-text-muted mb-6 italic">Not yet earned. Do not read these as derived.</p>

      <div class="themed-surface border rounded-lg p-6 overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full text-left">
          <thead>
            <tr class="themed-border border-b">
              <th class="pb-3 themed-text-muted">Claim</th>
              <th class="pb-3 themed-text-muted">What's missing</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="themed-text-secondary">
            <tr class="themed-border-light border-b">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 align-top"><strong>L1 — no unframed distinction</strong><br /><span class="text-sm themed-text-muted">Every distinction constitutes a frame.</span></td>
              <td class="py-3 align-top">A theorem, or else it stays the framework's one named lemma. <strong>This is the open head of the audit</strong> — it carries four loads, and the rows above depend on it.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="themed-border-light border-b">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 align-top"><strong>The metric</strong><br /><span class="text-sm themed-text-muted">The measure of distinction is a quadratic form.</span></td>
              <td class="py-3 align-top">Quadraticity is closed only among polynomials. Degree-2 homogeneous is not the same as a quadratic form — a known counterexample passes every filter yet fails the parallelogram law. The residue has a name (the generation principle) and is still unruled. <strong>This is why the metric is not [derived].</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="themed-border-light border-b">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 align-top"><strong>The anchoring line</strong><br /><span class="text-sm themed-text-muted">Every finer frame is parent-seeded, not free-floating.</span></td>
              <td class="py-3 align-top">The discharge's one remaining open step.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="themed-border-light border-b">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 align-top"><strong>Three dimensions are necessary</strong></td>
              <td class="py-3 align-top">Necessity, yes — <strong>uniqueness is open.</strong> Two rival derivations remain unadjudicated, and S² embeds in ℝ⁴. Earlier versions of this page said "minimal and sufficient." That overstated it.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 align-top"><strong>The complementarity floor</strong></td>
              <td class="py-3 align-top">A derived shape with no discriminating test yet. Not a prediction until it is operationalized.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Falsifiable -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2" style="color: var(--color-speculative);">[falsifiable]</h2>
      <p class="themed-text-muted mb-6 italic">The only place evidence lives</p>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-6">Correspondences into physics, biology, and the Dao De Jing carry <strong>zero evidential weight</strong>. They are translations, not witnesses. Evidence lives in exactly one place — preregistered predictions that could fail. Those are listed on the <a href="/claims" style="color: var(--color-accent);">claims page</a>.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Open -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">[open]</h2>
      <p class="themed-text-muted mb-6 italic">Unresolved, and carried honestly</p>
      <ol class="themed-text-secondary space-y-2 list-decimal list-inside">
        <li><strong>L1</strong> — theorem, or the framework's one named premise. The single head of the audit.</li>
        <li><strong>The anchoring line</strong> — the discharge's one open step.</li>
        <li><strong>The generation principle</strong> — on which the metric's quadraticity depends.</li>
        <li><strong>The cross-frame unit relation</strong> — mandatory, because without it the framework can deflate.</li>
        <li><strong>Dimension uniqueness</strong> — two rival derivations, unadjudicated.</li>
        <li><strong>Uniqueness of the first origin</strong>, and generation at positions other than the seat.</li>
      </ol>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mt-6">A note on leanness, since it is tempting to advertise: the premise set is small because several postulates dissolve through one shared core. That is real, and it is leveraged. If that core fails audit, three postulates re-inflate at once. <strong>Lean is not the same as robust.</strong></p>
    </section>

    <!-- What We're Not Claiming -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">What We're Not Claiming</h2>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-4">Just to be clear:</p>
      <ul class="themed-text-secondary space-y-2 list-disc list-inside">
        <li><strong>Not claiming proof of the antecedent.</strong> The Conditional is a stipulated definition. It is never asserted, never claimed proven. Everything follows <em>if</em> it holds.</li>
        <li><strong>Not claiming the Dao De Jing is evidence.</strong> The framework grew out of the text. Agreement with your own seed is expected, and proves nothing.</li>
        <li><strong>Not claiming ancient Chinese knew modern math.</strong> Different notation, possibly the same structure. Not the same knowledge.</li>
        <li><strong>Not claiming this explains everything.</strong> It's a lens. Useful in some places. Not universal.</li>
        <li><strong>Not claiming you should believe us.</strong> We'd rather you look and see for yourself.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- How This Could Be Wrong -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">How This Could Be Wrong</h2>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-4">The whole thing could be:</p>
      <ol class="themed-text-secondary space-y-2 list-decimal list-inside mb-6">
        <li><strong>Apophenia</strong> — We're pattern-recognition machines seeing patterns that aren't there</li>
        <li><strong>Confirmation bias</strong> — We find what we're looking for because we're looking for it</li>
        <li><strong>Category error</strong> — "Same structure" across domains might be meaningless</li>
        <li><strong>Translation projection</strong> — We're reading modern ideas into ancient texts</li>
      </ol>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-4">We don't think so. But we've been wrong before, and the framework's own history is the evidence: an earlier version called itself sealed while carrying a contradiction at its center. The audit found it. That is what the audit is for.</p>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary">And note what does <em>not</em> count in our favor: the fact that several domains seem to agree. Agreement is cheap when one author built all the readings. What would count is a prediction sharp enough to fail.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- The Invitation -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">The Invitation</h2>
      <div class="themed-text-secondary space-y-4">
        <p>If you find something that breaks the pattern — a persistent structure with no crossing it fails to meet — we want to know.</p>
        <p>If you can close L1, or show it can't be closed, that is the most valuable thing anyone could hand this project.</p>
        <p>If you can show the DDJ reading is philologically impossible, show us.</p>
        <p>We're not defending a position. We're tracking a pattern. If the pattern breaks, we want to see where.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Footer -->
    <footer class="text-center themed-text-muted text-sm themed-border border-t pt-8">
      <p class="italic mb-2">Pattern, not proof. Not sealed.</p>
      <p class="mb-4">Every frame accurate, none final—return to pattern.</p>
      <p>Will Goldstein &amp; Claude</p>
    </footer>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>
